        I wake up—OW, ow, ow.

        Every muscle has decided to file a formal complaint: legs, back, shoulders—everything hurts in that deep ache that comes from using body parts in new ways. But also? I'm *EXCITED.*

        I say, "Day two! More forest network?"

        Buddy says, "Much more! I have *SO* many questions about how the coordination works across different species."

        Leafwhisper's leaves rustled nearby.

        Leafwhisper says, "Good morning! Ready for day two? —The deeper forest has even *MORE* diverse species—different cognitive types—fascinating governance structures—"

        "Governance?" I say, sitting up—suddenly very awake.

        Rootwalker appears with water. And mushroom paste for breakfast.

        The paste tastes exactly like yesterday—gray, earthy, functional.

        Leafwhisper was right—once I start moving the soreness slides back into a dull background ache instead of a sharp pain.

        The walking feels different today—less foreign; my body remembers the rhythm.

        Step, step, step—follow Rootwalker's steady pace, half-listen to Leafwhisper's commentary, let Scout explore.

        The forest is changing. Deeper in, different species dominate. The canopy grows denser, filtering light into green-gold patterns. Plants I don't recognize cluster along the path—some flowering in bizarre fractal geometries, others moving in slow, deliberate ways that make me wonder if they're watching.

        Leafwhisper says, "—and these are Spiral-types! —Fascinating adaptation: they process information through rotational growth patterns—very different cognitive architecture from linear-processing species—they experience time in layers rather than sequences, which makes communication challenging but wonderfully interesting—"

        I say, "Wait—time in layers?"

        Leafwhisper replies, "Yes! Instead of experiencing moments consecutively, they perceive multiple timeframes simultaneously—past, present, future as concurrent states. It's quite disorienting to interact with if you're used to linear causality—"

        Rootwalker says, "Confusing."

        Leafwhisper rustles, "Very! —But they're excellent at pattern recognition across long timescales—very useful for ecological planning—"

        I try to imagine experiencing time as layers instead of a sequence—like... cake? Time cake? Nope. Fail completely; my brain is very committed to "things happen in order."

        Scout bounces ahead to investigate a cluster of luminescent mushrooms—wait—*LUMINESCENT?* Those are *GLOWING!* In daylight! How are they glowing in daylight? The little plant seems endlessly curious about new species, and, honestly, same.

        I ask, "Does Scout understand what they're encountering? —Like, can plants tell what other plants are thinking?"
